args:
With rehearsal in full swing, Laxi learns that
people can put their hearts into anything.
But the day before opening night, Marley
hears that his sister is in critical condition,
bringing the production to a standstill.
You are in love with Carol, Dr. Schmidt.\nMy body is nothing more than a vessel\nfor her heart.
Yet I was born instead. I am a failure\nwho replaced Carol's heart.

I am a defective creation that got between
you two—one who knows only jealousy.
It would be best if I were to simply
disappear.
Fran, wait. You are, um...you are\nno failed experiment.
I was thinking of no one but myself when\nI created you to bring my beloved Carol\nback from the dead...
Excellent work, you two! Excellent!\nAh, but my heart sings!
(I knew this would happen.\nI can't act at all.)
Marley, I would like to make some\nchanges to the script.
Ha ha! Now you're sounding like a star!\nSo what do you want changed, my dear?
The clockwork creature does not know the\nname of many emotions. It is unnatural\nfor her to say she knows ＂jealousy.＂
Hmm... Yes, I suppose I can see that.\nThank you for giving me that perspective.
(And now she's even found something\nin common with her character!)

(Well, that's all there is to it. I'll just have
to find something in common with MY
character and use that to boost my own
acting chops.)
Places, everyone! Places! Sylas, I want to\nrun the next scene—your monologue.
I have immersed myself in all manner of\nresearch! Resurrecting the dead, miracle\ndrugs...anything that might save my Carol.
Yet somewhere, somehow...\nI strayed down the wrong path.
I wanted only to save her. That was my\nsole purpose. I loved her more than life,\nand yet she died in agony.
(I knew I was right to cast him!)
▷You and Marley really came alive\nduring that rehearsal!◁
Yes. The new script is coming along\nquite nicely.
I can feel the heart within this play\nmore than ever.
▷Me too. The more you and Sylas add\nyour thoughts to it, the better it gets.◁
▷I think that's because you're all pouring\nyour hearts into it.◁
Pouring our hearts... It's so mysterious.\n▷Uh, it is?◁
Affirmative. The heart is merely an organ\nused to maintain various bodily functions.
A human brain may differ in shape and\ndisposition, but it effectively works the\nsame way as our hearts.
Yet hearts are more than mere organs.\nThey come to dwell in the things that\npeople pour them into.
It has no form; it is not something one can\nmake through the gathering of materials.\nI understand that now.
▷The creators of the combat androids\nmust have gone to great trouble to make\nthe ego circuits we know as hearts.◁
Unknown. But I want to see Marley's\nexpression when he finally looks upon his\nfinished creation.
It's all I can think of right now.
Because it may lead me to understand\nwhat Maestro felt when he made us.
▷The script is almost finished!\nOoo, I'm so excited!◁\nAffirmative.
Sorry to keep you waiting, Laxi,\nbut we're going to wrap for today.
▷Huh? Already?◁\nThere's still daylight.\nWhy are we stopping?
I must finish the script, so I need to bend\nmy will to an all-night writing session.
Then the finale is truly upon us.\nI look forward to tomorrow.
Get ready to have your socks blown clean\noff your feet at tomorrow's rehearsal!
(Ah, but my creative juices are flowing!\nAt this rate, I can finish before dawn.)
You're from the hospital! What are you\ndoing here at this time of night?
...Incomprehensible. Where is Marley?\n▷Yeah, it's already noon.◁
We can't very well rehearse without him.
We'll go to his house. I will be very\nangry with him if he's sleeping in.
No response... Do you think he's out?
Negative. I detect signs of movement.\nHe's inside.\n▷So why won't he come out?◁
I will break down the door.\n▷Huh? Laxi, no! Wait!◁
▷You really did it. Oh geez...◁\nLet us go, Sylas.
Marley? What happened today?\nDid you not finish the script?
Script? Who cares about some script?
I received word from the hospital\nlast night.
Shelley is in critical condition, and her\nchances of recovery are slim. The next few\ndays will determine if she lives or dies.
I came all this way just to make her happy.
But now she's going to die anyway and I...\nI can't...
Enough, Laxi. Let us leave him be.
Sylas, is Marley not going to write the rest\nof the script?
Shelley was his sole reason for writing\nthis play in the first place.
If she isn't there to see it, then...
Oh, this is a disaster! A DISASTER!
Marley just contacted me and said he's\nnot going to finish the script!
What are we going to do for our big\nHalloween performance now?!
I waited this long because the public\nalways loves his plays...
But there's no salvaging this.\nWe'll have to cancel.
